## North Star

Build a community around E.I. Werner as a fantasy writer and creative leader that makes the writing career financially sustainable and less lonely. The room full of people who chose to care about the things done alone for 18 years. That room has a name: The Outside Inn. Motivate people to fully commit to their own dreams through the undimmed passion of an 18-year grind with almost nothing to show for it — and give fantasy lovers, productive gamers, and writers in the trenches a front-row seat to how the work actually gets made, with real opportunities to engage and contribute along the way. So that when the books are ready, the audience is already there and already cares.

**Community is the engine. Everything else serves it.**

When in doubt about any strategic decision, return to this hierarchy: does it grow the community, deepen it, or sustain the person building it? If not, deprioritize it.

**What Evan must be known for:**

A fantasy author who actually builds his world in public. Someone who has been going for 18 years without external validation and is still going. A leader with earnest charisma who lifts people up around the things the world told them to downplay.

**What he must consistently do:**

Stream live, writing into gaming, three times a week. Build the ONCE mythology in public. Say the brand statement until the audience says it back. Be the proof of concept.

---

## Who He Is

Evan Ilan Werner. Goes by E.I. Werner for his writing. A mythwright — someone who builds the myths first, then the world that needs them. Decided at 15 he would be a fantasy author — not wanted to be, decided. That decision has organized nearly everything since: nearly two decades of writing almost every day, career moves designed to fund the art, a creative project of genuinely unusual ambition that is still in progress and still getting bigger.

He has a published tabletop game credit. He landed a literary agent for a completed fantasy novel that went out to every major publisher on earth. He co-wrote a feature screenplay about the first marathon runner in ancient Athens. He is not a hobbyist. He is a working writer who has not yet published a book.

That gap — nearly two decades of real, serious work and almost nothing to show for it in the way the world measures — is not tragedy. It is proof. It is the brand.

He was student body president. Captain of teams. He chose the nerdy path from a position of not needing to. That choice reads.

His rebel instinct runs deep: when everyone goes one way, he tends to go the other. This is often a superpower.

**E.I. Werner is not a pen name.** It is the version of himself that could matter. The writing is the person. They are not separable.

---

## Brand Statement & Sign-Off

> **Brand Statement:** "Writing, fantasy, and games are not escapes. They are destinations."

> **Sign-Off:** "While you're here, you're already there."

These are not slogans. They are positions. The brand statement contradicts the mainstream framing of an entire genre and can be defended from the mythology up. Fantasy is not where you go to avoid the world. It is one of the few places where certain truths can be stated directly — truths that realism can only approximate. The greatest fantasy has always known this.

The sign-off closes every stream. It does the same work as the brand statement but in the present tense — the destination is not coming, it is here now, in the community, in the room.

Say the brand statement until the audience says it back. The proof that it is working is when they start defending it without being asked.

---

## The Three Audiences & Their Pain

The brand serves three overlapping audiences. They often exist in the same person. The through-line across all three: people who are slowly shrinking away from something they love because they don't have the language, the community, or the permission to stay in it fully. E.I. Werner is the place where they don't have to shrink.

---

### Audience 1 — The Fantasy Lover

*Someone who has had to apologize for what they love their entire life.*

They feel guilty about the time they spend reading or watching fantasy. They can't explain to people why it matters without sounding childish. They don't have anyone in their life who wants to go deep on this stuff with them. They've outgrown most fantasy content creators — too juvenile, too focused on ranking other people's work. They want someone building something new, not reviewing someone else's.

**Cost of inaction:** They slowly shrink away from something that shaped them. Quiet self-betrayal.

---

### Audience 2 — The Productive Gamer

*Someone who games seriously and carries guilt about it because the world told them to.*

They're ambitious and productive but assume gamers are lazy. They want to game but can't justify it when they feel behind on everything else. They can't find people who game with intention, not just to waste time.

**Cost of inaction:** They keep shrinking a real source of joy. Neither stopping nor continuing sustainably.

---

### Audience 3 — The Writer in the Trenches

*Someone grinding at something nobody believes in yet, or who gave up because the sacrifice got too heavy.*

They feel completely alone in the grind. No one understands what they've sacrificed. They don't know if what they're doing is crazy or courageous. They need to see someone who is still going in order to believe they can keep going.

**What E.I. Werner provides to this audience:** Not advice. Not craft instruction. Visible proof that someone is still going. 18 years deep. Still here. That is the value.

---

## Differentiation — The Contrarian Positions

| What the Space Says / Does | The E.I. Werner Position |
|---|---|
| Fantasy creators review and rank other people's work | He builds his own. The ONCE mythology is the content — not commentary on someone else's. |
| Success stories dominate creator culture | He documents the grind without mainstream success — and treats that as the differentiator, not the liability. |
| Authenticity is performed | His 18-year record is the authenticity. The rejection ledger is public. The process is live on screen. There's nowhere to hide. |
| "Escape" is how fantasy gets framed | Fantasy is a destination. Not a temporary exit. A place with its own truth and gravity. |
| Gaming is a guilty pleasure | Gaming is a legitimate form of community and connection. Full stop. No apology. |
| Writers should be famous before building an audience | A working writer — not yet published, not yet famous — can build an audience around the process itself if that process is real and visible. |
| Worldbuilding is backstage | The mythology is the content. ONCE is shareable now. The world exists before the book. |
| Content creators maintain distance | He games with the community. He writes with the community watching. The relationship is participatory. |
| Virality is the goal | Trust is the goal. He is not building a following. He is building a room. |
| Go wide to grow | He goes deep. The right 100 people in the room are worth more than 10,000 strangers who don't care. |

---

## Desired Associations

**What E.I. Werner should be known FOR:**

1. **Craft with soul** — the writing is the real thing, and it shows. Not content. Not product. Work.
2. **Permission to love what you love** — fantasy, gaming, the weird nerdy thing you've been downplaying. You're allowed.
3. **Endurance** — 18 years. Still going. That is the most powerful thing about this brand and it requires no embellishment.

**What E.I. Werner should be known AGAINST:**

1. **Content for content's sake** — every stream serves the writing or the community.
2. **Fantasy and gaming as lesser things** — he will not minimize them, qualify them, or frame them as "just" anything.
3. **Complaining instead of adapting** — the rejections are public but they are not the story. The continuation is.

---

## The Outside Inn — Its Role in the Brand

**E.I. Werner is who you are. The Outside Inn is where your people go.**

Someone finds you through the work — a stream, a video, a clip. That's E.I. Werner. If they care enough to go deeper, they end up inside The Outside Inn — the Discord, the membership, the community. The inn is the place that exists because of the work. You can't have the inn without the writer who built it. One world. Two sides of the same door.

E.I. Werner is the creator — the work, the streams, the public face, the name on the door. The Outside Inn is what's behind it. Not a second brand. Not a competing presence. The community layer of the same world.

The community needs a name, and "the E.I. Werner community" is a description, not a place. The Outside Inn is a place. The Discord is the lobby. The warmup and cooldown bookends every stream — the inn as a felt experience before and after the work. The membership tiers describe what someone is in relation to the place, not just the work. You're not filing a credential. You pulled up a stool.

---

## ONCE — The Mythology

> **Logline:** Seven original myths braid astrophysics, philosophy, and religion into a single, foundational hymn — tracing humanity's emergence from before the Beginning.

Seven original creation myths forming the complete cosmology of a fantasy world. Not worldbuilding notes. A moral philosophy built from scratch, with answers to the questions every civilization must answer: What are we for? What is evil? What happens when we die? What do we owe each other?

This is the first product the brand will deliver to the world. It is also the primary shareable content until the novel exists. The mythology is not backstage — it is the show. ONCE is shareable now. The world exists before the book.

**The seven hymns:** ONCE, MOTHER, BROTHER, WAR, GATE, CHOSEN, KEEPER.

KEEPER shares a name with the retired novel. The connection is intentional and runs deep.

---

## Community & Membership

The community of E.I. Werner lives inside The Outside Inn. Everything runs through Fourthwall. One platform, one brand experience. Three tiers: a free lobby and two paid tiers that describe what someone is in relation to the place, not just the work.

### Free Tier — The Lobby
*Everyone who finds the door.*

- Access to the general Discord
- Luiz art optimized as desktop/phone wallpapers (attribution to Outside Inn Studios)

### Innsider — $7.77/month
*The community tier. Pull up a stool.*

- Exclusive Innsider Discord channel
- 14% merch discount (auto-applied at checkout)
- Early access to limited edition drops
- Vote on stream topics (writing and gaming)
- Monthly patron-only livestream (Innsiders + Innkeeps)
- Name in video and stream credits, rolling in join order
- Innsider-only videos *(coming — not at launch)*
- Founding Innsider badge — first 777, numbered, permanent

### Innkeep — $21.21/month
*The inner circle. The back table.*

Everything in Innsider, plus:

- Innkeep-only Discord channel
- Signal group with Evan
- 21% merch discount (auto-applied at checkout)
- Exclusive merch drops announced in Signal first
- Name in video and stream credits, visually distinct from Innsiders, rolling in join order
- Writing review after 7 consecutive months — 777 words, live on stream *(coming — not at launch)*
- Founding Innkeep badge — first 77, numbered, permanent (~10 pre-assigned)

### The Pricing Logic

$7.77 and $21.21. Base-7 runs through the fantasy world — a septimal numeral system woven through the cosmology, the creation myths, and the community structure. The prices carry that DNA. The discounts (14% and 21%) follow the same logic. Everything in this brand is divisible by seven.

### Credit Roll Logic

All members — Innsiders and Innkeeps — roll in video and stream credits in order of joining. Number 1 joined before number 2. Lower numbers are earlier. Innkeeps are visually distinct from Innsiders in the roll — the distinction is design-level, not loud. The visual language is to be finalized with Luiz or Marwan before the patron roll goes live.

### The Growth Funnel

Growth is sequenced, not simultaneous.

**Layer 1 — Deputize the homies.** The founding members are co-owners of the culture. They recruit because they are proud of the place, not because they were asked. This layer never stops.

**Layer 2 — Warm network.** Existing connections who already like Evan but don't yet know this exists. Personal outreach converts far above cold. LinkedIn is underrated — the PM background, building something unusual, is a story people share.

**Layer 3 — Vertical clips.** The scale lever. The clip machine turns streams into discovery. This is how new people find the room when they weren't already connected to Evan. Streams have to be worth clipping before this layer activates.

