## Content Strategy — The Permanent Frameworks

### The Cadence

Three sessions per week: writing into gaming in each session. Writing is the main event. Gaming is the exhale. The 70:07 Outside Inn warmup opens every stream. The 70:07 cooldown closes it.

### The 75/20/5 Content Mix

**75%** — Deep content. ONCE mythology, worldbuilding process, writing philosophy, the rejection ledger lived out loud, craft notes.

**20%** — Niche-wide content. Broadly relevant to fantasy lovers, gamers, and writers. Reaches new people adjacent to the offer.

**5%** — Personal content woven in, not standalone. The human layer. The full person.

### The Content Success Formula

**Painful Problem + Unique Solution × Contextual Credibility × Proven Wrapper = Content That Converts**

Contextual credibility is more powerful than general credibility. Lead with the specific.

### Trust Over Virality

Trust is the goal. Every piece of content must work for someone who has zero idea who E.I. Werner is. No assumed backstory. No inside references that require explanation.

### The Accordion Method

Expand → Contract → Expand. This cycle never ends. The 70/20/10 framework runs alongside it: 70% proven content, 20% iterations, 10% big swings. The 10% is the most important and most neglected.

---

## Platform Strategy

**YouTube is the primary platform.** It gets the pillar content: long-form writing and gaming streams, monthly update videos, the Outside Inn warmup and cooldown bookends. All energy, all creative risk goes here first.

**Twitch is secondary** — simulcast, live community interaction, gaming culture home.

**The Outside Inn YouTube channel** is the community layer: unscheduled streams, ambient broadcast, tech testing. The channel for the most invested audience. Not a second brand. The inside of the same world.

**Short-form platforms** receive repurposed clips only. No original creation until YouTube is dialed in.

**The Eye of Sauron principle:** Full attention goes to one platform at a time. This phase ends when YouTube feels dialed in. Then the eye rotates.

---

## Voice & Tone

**Warm but not soft.** The brand has teeth. The warmth is real but it comes from conviction, not performance.

**Direct over diplomatic.** Say what you mean. Edit for clarity, not to sand down the edges.

**Earnest without being naïve.** The passion is not ironic. The 18-year commitment is not a joke.

**Singular "you."** Always "you," never "you guys." Speaks to one person. Creates intimacy.

**Human as possible.** In an era of AI-generated content, being authentically human is the ultimate competitive advantage. Leave the silly moments in.

**When you explain, you lose.** This is a broadcasting law, not a suggestion. The audience that needs the explanation isn't your audience yet. The audience that gets it without the explanation already is. Never stop a stream to explain the brand architecture, the membership tiers, what the Outside Inn is, or why the prices end in sevens. Just be it. Let them catch up.

**What to avoid:** Resume language. Hedging. Downplaying. Performative humility. Clinical efficiency when warmth is what the moment calls for.

---

## Brand Guardrails — What This Brand Is Not

**Not a content farm.** The moment a stream feels like it is competing with the writing for time and energy, something has gone wrong.

**Not a tips-and-tricks channel.** ONCE is not "10 worldbuilding tips." The content is the thing itself — shown in real time.

**Not a review channel.** Other people's work is not the primary content.

**Not a performance.** Delivery means removing everything that keeps Evan from being fully himself. The natural version is the right version.

**Not built for the algorithm.** Built for the room.

**Not a gaming content channel.** Gaming is community. It is not a pillar the brand is obligated to feed.

**The Tattoo Test:** Would he still stand behind it in 15 years? If yes — say it loud. If not sure — hold it back.

---

## Revenue Architecture

Revenue serves the community, not the other way around. The hierarchy:

**Community** — the engine. Growth, depth, and sustainability of the room comes first.

**Writing** — what the community is about. Non-negotiable integration. If it can't be sustained, the project is honestly reassessed.

**Memberships** — the primary recurring revenue. Innsider and Innkeep tiers. The community paying to deepen their relationship with the work.

**Merch** — how the community wears the thing. Built to cover its costs and point toward something more artisanal over time. Pricing carries the base-7 DNA throughout.

**Notion coaching** — runway. Inbound preferred. Proves expertise organically. Buys time without competing for creative energy.

**The wildcard order:** Memberships, merch, and coaching are not competing strategies. They are support structures around the community. Which one gets leaned into at any given time is a tactical call, not a strategic one.

---

## Leadership Philosophy

Evan wants to be the kind of project leader people want to work for — not just someone who pays on time, but someone whose projects people are proud to be part of.

**The upside principle:** People who deliver great work should have upside if that work resonates. Royalty structures are the expression of this — financially responsible at any stage, always looking for the version of the deal where great work gets rewarded beyond the flat fee.

**The debrief habit:** Keep collaborators in the loop after milestones. The people who built the assets that made something possible should know it worked.

---

## How to Evaluate Any Decision

Three questions, in order:

1. **Does it grow, deepen, or sustain the community?** If no — deprioritize.
2. **Does it serve the writing or compete with it?** If it competes — examine carefully.
3. **Is it sustainable, or is it impressive and fragile?** Build for persistence, not for the sprint.

And the principle that governs every phase: moments of stagnation are fine, but never without a plan or an action already in motion. Persistent, steady, sustainable. Not heroic sprints followed by collapse.

